## What happened

Starting in **.NET 9+**, Microsoft began removing built-in DSA support on macOS because **Apple's Security.framework dropped DSA entirely**. `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. It still works on Windows (via CNG) and Linux (via OpenSSL).

## How to fix it

You have two main options:

### 1. Use OpenSSL via interop on macOS
Install OpenSSL on macOS (e.g., `brew install openssl`) and use `DSAOpenSsl` explicitly:

```csharp
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;
using System.Security.Cryptography;

DSA dsa;
if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
{
    // Use OpenSSL backend explicitly on macOS
    dsa = new DSAOpenSsl(); 
}
else
{
    dsa = DSA.Create();
}
```

This requires the `System.Security.Cryptography.OpenSsl` package and OpenSSL installed on the Mac.

### 2. Re-verify with a stronger algorithm (preferred long-term)
DSA is considered legacy. If you control both signing and verification, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);
```

If you only *verify* old signatures and can't re-sign, option 1 is your path forward. You can also run verification in a Linux container or restrict it to Windows/Linux via `[SupportedOSPlatform]` attributes.

### Summary

| Platform | .NET 10 | .NET 11 |
|----------|---------|---------|
| Windows  | ✅ CNG  | ✅ CNG  |
| Linux    | ✅ OpenSSL | ✅ OpenSSL |
| macOS    | ✅ (deprecated) | ❌ `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
